    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a clear priority on speed and exploitable matchups, anchored by the day\u2019s highest projection, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98). While **Pete Crow-Armstrong** typically suffers from his #8 slotting, his matchup against Chase Petty (xERA 6.57) provides a massive +19% boost to his efficiency, making him a locked-in must-start despite the lineup position. Joining him at the top of our high-confidence tier is **Trea Turner** (66.43). **Trea Turner** benefits from a prime leadoff opportunity against Junk; his ability to capitalize on SB scarcity makes his favorable lineup placement paramount, as he is the primary engine for our stolen base category today. \n\nStrategic platoon edges are driving much of our mid-tier production. **Dillon Dingler** (56.77) and **Junior Caminero** (63.97) both navigate their respective matchups against southpaws efficiently, with **Dillon Dingler** receiving a +14% boost from a dynamic platoon advantage. Conversely, we are keeping a close eye on **Carson Benge** (67.24). While his projected score is excellent due to a soft matchup against Sugano and favorable park factors, the 34% rain risk serves as a non-trivial volatility flag that could derail his plate appearances. For the bench decision, **Colt Keith** (42.25) narrowly held the UTIL spot over other reserves, though his negative platoon shift against Tolle highlights the volatility of the bottom end of our lineup. We are also monitoring the status of **Christian Yelich**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Caleb Durbin**, **Zac Veen**, **Josh Smith**, **Luis Pena**, and **Pedro Ramirez**, all of whom remain unavailable or off-roster today as we manage our daily game caps to ensure we don't bleed points from sub-optimal starts.\n\nBeyond these core plays, we must highlight the high-floor reliability of **Yordan Alvarez** (60.60). Despite drawing a difficult assignment against Yoshinobu Yamamoto, **Yordan Alvarez** maintains elite status due to his xwOBA of 0.427, proving that his raw hitting talent overcomes most SP-skill penalties. We have also factored in wind-assisted projections for **Gary Sanchez** (49.95) and **Chase Meidroth** (44.38); both players get a +5% boost from wind-out conditions, which helps stabilize their scoring in otherwise marginal matchups. While **Kazuma Okamoto** (57.82) is a solid play against Martinez, we remain cautious regarding the overall lineup construction until official announcements confirm the status of **Gary Sanchez**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Chase Meidroth**, **Trea Turner**, **Kyle Schwarber**, **Luke Raley**, **Yordan Alvarez**, and **Pete Crow-Armstrong**.",
